Pearson Correlation Coefficient

Null Hypothesis: There is a correlation between the HDL and alcohol consumption.

H0: p = 0

Alternative Hypothesis: There is no correlation between HDL and the consumption of alcohol.

HA: p ≠ 0

alpha level = 0.05

Above is a scatter plot of HDL levels verses alcohol consumption. The line going through the graph is the calculated pearson coefficient below. As we can see there is a slight positive correlation based on the coefficient. Most of the data appears to clump together towards the beginning of the graph not making it clear if there is a correlation or not when not taking the r line into account.

library(stats)

corr_coe <- cor.test(monica3$hdl, monica3$alcohol)

print(corr_coe)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  monica3$hdl and monica3$alcohol
## t = 24.298, df = 4895, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.3028475 0.3528409
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.3280739

The correlation between the HDL and alcohol was calculated to be .328. The HDL and alcohol were moderately low in terms of correlation. The p-value(~0) and t-statistic(24.298) indicate that they are statistically significant. Based of the very low p-value and very high t-statistic, we can reject the null hypothesis of there being a correlation between the two factors. The correlation value r = .328 indicates how little the alcohol consumption per week does effects the HDL levels. In conclusion HDL levels do not have a correlation with how much alcohol one drinks in a week.

Normality of the HDL Cholesterol

The graph below is a normal distribution Q-Q plot, which demonstrates how well the data falls into the normal distribution. As we can see, most of the data point on the plot follow closely with the theoretical line. This indicates that data follows the normal distribution. There is a slight curve to the data points on each end, those don’t hold as much weight as the majority of the data falls within the middle on the theoretical line.
